what: R Wrapper to Access the OpenAlex API
title: R Wrapper to Access the OpenAlex API
text: goal openalexR create R wrapper Open Alex API (https://openalex.org) allows users query extract results Open Alex database academic research output. Open Alex succeeds Microsoft Academic Graph maintaining extensive relational database. API 5 endpoints query: (1) Works (journal & conference papers, books, data, etc); (2) Authors; (3) Venues; (4) Institutions; (5) Concepts. information endpoints can found : (https://docs.openalex.org). API completely free, open source, rate limits. prefer, can also request snapshot data copied amazon s3 bucket (https://docs.openalex.org/download-snapshot). openalexR functions request data five endpoints: get_works, get_authors, get_venues, get_institutions, get_concepts. also wrapper functions specific needs (get_authors_papers, get_coauthors).

title: R Wrapper to Access the OpenAlex API
text: can install development version openalexR GitHub :

title: R Wrapper to Access the OpenAlex API
text: find_works function takes three main parameters: (1) ID type, one : doi, open_alex, mag (Microsoft Academic Graph), pmid (Pubmed Identifier), pmcid (Pubmed Central Identifier) (2) Id(s), can either 1 id list ids. (3) Variable_unnest (optional) - variable like make dataframe longer (can : authorships, concepts, referenced_works, related_works, citation_counts_year) example, wanted look paper “Analysis glottal excitation emotionally styled stressed speech” Kathleen E. Cummings (mom!) Mark . Clements, can use doi (https://doi.org/10.1121/1.413664) shown : function returns tibble nested columns. decided unnest authorships column, can extract openalex id Kathleen E. Cummings use retrieve published work (get_authors_papers) coauthorship network (get_coauthors). get_authors_papers() function works similarly find_work - need indicate type id supplying id . use openalex id got previous result. can explore results – look distribution concepts across published work.  Finally, can also use get_coauthors() function collect coauthorship network specified author choice.

all_papers %>%      unnest(concepts, names_sep = "_") %>%      group_by(concepts_display_name, concepts_level) %>%      summarise(count = n()) %>%      ggplot(mapping = aes(x = reorder(concepts_display_name, count), y = count)) +      geom_col() + coord_flip() + facet_wrap(~concepts_level, scales = "free_y") +     theme_minimal() + labs(title = "Concepts in published papers",                            subtitle = "by concept specificity level (lower is broader)",                            x = "concept name", y = "number of papers") #> `summarise()` has grouped You can override #> using the `.groups` argument. kate_direct_coauthors <- get_coauthors(id_type = "openalex",                                        id = mom_oa_id) #> Joining, by = "ego_author"  coauthors_tibble <- get_coauthors(id_type = "openalex",                                    id = unique(kate_direct_coauthors$alter_author)) #> Joining, by = "ego_author"  only_ego_net <- coauthors_tibble %>% filter(alter_author %in% kate_direct_coauthors$alter_author)  all_connections <- bind_rows(kate_direct_coauthors, only_ego_net) %>%                     dplyr::mutate(ego_first = paste(ego_author_name, alter_author_name, sep = "_"),                           alter_first = paste(alter_author_name, alter_author_name, sep = "_")) %>%                     tidyr::pivot_longer(ego_first:alter_first,                                  names_to = "order",                                  values_to = "tie") %>%                    dplyr::select(paper_id, tie) %>%                    dplyr::distinct() %>% separate(tie, into = c("ego_author",                                                                "alter_author"), sep = "_") %>%                    filter(ego_author != alter_author) %>%                    group_by(ego_author, alter_author) %>%                    summarise(weight = n()) #> `summarise()` has grouped output by 'ego_author'. title: Get Authors Papers — get_authors_papers
text: dataframe papers author, includes variables: id: openalex id paper display_name: title paper publication date: date publication YYYY-MM-DD form relevance score: ?sure , NA atm authorships: nested dataframe authors paper (includes author.id, author_position, author.display_name, author.orcid) concepts: nested dataframe concepts associated paper (includes openalex's id concept, display.name concept, score concept, level concept concept hierarchy, wikidata concept) alternate_host_venues: ?sure either, need check openalex's page cited_by_count: number papers cited paper publication_year: int cited_by_api_url: openalex api url papers cited paper doi: doi paper type: type paper (e.g. proceedings-article, journal-article, book-chapter, posted-content) is_paratext: ?sure either, need check openalex's page is_retracted: TRUE/FALSE whether paper retracted referenced_works: list works referenced paper (openalex urls :) ) related_works: similar works? sure found
